### 2. `log_many()` — multiple violations for one record

Best when one logical record fails several rules (e.g. `person_nbr` is null **and** `i_mode` is invalid). All violations share one `response_id` and `event_type`, and are stamped with a single shared timestamp so they can be grouped as one validation pass.

```python
logger.log_many(
    violations,           # required: iterable of Violation
    *,
    event_type,           # required
    response_id=None,
    case_id=None,
    stack_trace=None,
)
```

Returns `None`.

A `Violation` carries:

| Field | Required | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `rule` | Yes | Registered rule name (resolved at log time). |
| `variable_name` | No | Variable that failed. None for FILE/RECORD-level. |
| `expected` | No | Expected value/pattern. Used for message generation only (not stored). |
| `message` | No | Per-violation message. If None, a default message is generated. |

```python
from utils.logger import Violation

violations = [
    Violation(rule="null_not_allowed", variable_name="person_nbr",
              message="person_nbr is required"),
    Violation(rule="invalid_enum", variable_name="i_mode",
              expected="Online | Phone | Visit"),
    Violation(rule="value_out_of_range", variable_name="i_age",
              expected="0..120"),
]

logger.log_many(
    violations,
    event_type="DATACONTRACTVALIDATION",
    response_id="P99999",
    case_id="CASE-999",
)
```

