### 3. `log_dataframe()` — bulk logging from a Spark DataFrame

Best for set-based validation that produces one row per failure (e.g. `df.filter(...)`).

```python
logger.log_dataframe(
    df,                            # required
    *,
    rule,                          # required
    event_type,                    # required
    variable_name=None,
    variable_name_column=None,
    expected=None,
    response_id_column,            # required
    case_id_column=None,
    collection_instance_id_column=None,
    message=None,
    message_column=None,
    stack_trace=None,
)
```

**Returns** the number of records appended to the buffer (`int`); `0` if the DataFrame is empty.

> **Driver-memory safety limit.** This method collects rows to the driver. If the DataFrame has more than **100,000 rows** it raises `ValueError`. Filter to actual failures (or split into batches) before calling.

**Per-row fields (DataFrame columns):**

| Parameter | Required | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `response_id_column` | Yes | Column holding the response ID for each row (e.g. `"person_nbr"`). |
| `case_id_column` | No | Column holding per-row case IDs. |
| `collection_instance_id_column` | No | Column holding per-row collection instance IDs. If omitted, the context value is used. |
| `variable_name_column` | No | Column naming the failed variable per row. Use when the DataFrame spans multiple variables. |
| `message_column` | No | Column holding a per-row message. |

**Constant fields (applied to every row):**

| Parameter | Required | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `rule` | Yes | Registry rule applied to all rows. |
| `event_type` | Yes | Event category applied to all rows. |
| `expected` | No | Constant expected value, for message generation only. |
| `variable_name` | No | Constant variable name (use when the whole DataFrame is one variable). |
| `message` | No | Constant message for all rows. |
| `stack_trace` | No | Constant traceback applied to all rows. |

**Message precedence:** `message_column` → `message` → auto-generated from `rule` (and `expected`).

**Mutual exclusivity** — passing both of a pair raises `ValueError`:
- `variable_name` and `variable_name_column`
- `message` and `message_column`

A missing `response_id_column`, or any named column not present in the DataFrame, also raises `ValueError`.

**Shape A — one-variable validation:**

```python
invalid_age_df = df.filter((df.i_age < 0) | (df.i_age > 120))

count = logger.log_dataframe(
    invalid_age_df,
    rule="value_out_of_range",
    event_type="DATACONTRACTVALIDATION",
    variable_name="i_age",
    expected="0..120",
    response_id_column="person_nbr",
    case_id_column="i_id",
)
```

**Shape B — multi-variable normalised failures:**

```python
logger.log_dataframe(
    failures_df,
    rule="null_not_allowed",
    event_type="DATACONTRACTVALIDATION",
    response_id_column="person_nbr",
    variable_name_column="failed_variable",
    message_column="failure_message",
    collection_instance_id_column="collectionInstance",
)
```

**Shape C — constant message override:**

```python
logger.log_dataframe(
    invalid_enum_df,
    rule="invalid_enum",
    event_type="DATACONTRACTVALIDATION",
    variable_name="i_mode",
    expected="Online | Phone | Visit",
    response_id_column="person_nbr",
    message="Response mode is not one of the allowed values.",
)
```

